---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Rugby Club Management App | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How we helped a Western Sydney rugby union club cut admin time by 60% with a custom member management app for iOS and Android.",

  industry: "Sports & Recreation",
  tags: ["Mobile App", "Member Management", "Payments", "Flutter", "Push Notifications"],

  title: "Rugby Club Management App",
  summary: "A NSW rugby union club replaced paper-based rosters and manual fee collection with a full member management platform — cutting admin time by 60%.",

  heroImageDescription: "Coach using a tablet to review team roster on the club management app, with players in the background on a rugby field",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "A mid-sized Western Sydney rugby union club with roughly 450 registered members across eight competitive teams, from under-8s through to senior men's and women's grades. Operating for 22 years, the club is one of the larger community clubs in its district competition and relies almost entirely on volunteer administrators to keep day-to-day operations running.",
  clientSize: "~450 members · Est. 2002",
  clientLocation: "Western Sydney, NSW",

  pullQuote: "Before the app, I was spending my entire Sunday evening chasing down parents for payment confirmations and copying names into a spreadsheet. Now I check a dashboard on my phone, and it's all just there. It's genuinely changed how much I enjoy being involved.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Club Registrar",
  pullQuoteRole: "Volunteer Administration, Rugby Union Club",

  challenge: [
    "The club had been running the same basic administrative processes for well over a decade. Player registrations were managed through paper forms collected at the start of each season, then manually transcribed into a shared Excel spreadsheet maintained by the volunteer registrar. The spreadsheet had grown organically over the years — different tabs for different grades, different colour-coding schemes applied by different people — and had reached the point where it was genuinely fragile. A corrupted file mid-season would have been a crisis.",
    "Fee collection was equally informal. The club accepted cash at training and direct bank transfers, with the registrar spending hours each week cross-referencing payment notifications against member names. Many families simply forgot, and following up felt awkward in a community setting where the registrar also stood on the sideline watching their own child play. By mid-season, outstanding fees often represented 15–20% of registered members, creating real cash-flow uncertainty for the club's purchasing decisions.",
    "Communications were fragmented across multiple WhatsApp group chats — one per team, some per grade, some ad hoc — with coaches, managers, and parents all mixing personal and club messages in the same threads. Coaches had no reliable way to check who was confirmed for training on a given night, and team managers had no visibility of whether a player had a current Working With Children Check on file, which was becoming an increasing concern given NSW regulatory expectations.",
    "The match-day experience compounded the frustration. Sign-on sheets were printed each week, carried to the field in plastic sleeves, collected at the end of matches, and then someone had to manually enter the attendance back into the spreadsheet at home. If sheets were lost or rained on, attendance data was simply gone. The club had also received informal feedback from their district that digital attendance records would become an expectation rather than an option within a couple of seasons."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The club's treasurer had worked with a colleague whose small business had used All Webbed Labs for a customer-facing web app. They weren't looking for a large agency with a formal tender process — they needed someone who would take the time to understand how a volunteer-run community club actually operates, and who wouldn't propose a solution that required a full-time IT coordinator to maintain. A referral-based conversation, a couple of discovery calls, and a site visit to a Saturday morning training session were enough for both sides to feel confident about moving forward.",
    "We were also honest in that early conversation about what wouldn't work. Off-the-shelf sports management platforms existed, but the ones we looked at together were either too expensive for a community club budget, required annual licensing fees that would grow uncomfortably as membership grew, or imposed workflows that didn't match how this club actually organised its grades and sub-committees. A custom build gave the club full ownership and the flexibility to extend the platform as its needs evolved."
  ],

  approach: [
    "We spent the first two weeks in discovery before writing a single line of code. That meant sitting in on a committee meeting, spending a Saturday at training watching how managers actually used clipboards and phones during warm-up, and conducting hour-long interviews with the registrar, three team managers, two coaches, and the treasurer. We came away with a detailed picture of workflows that weren't obvious from a surface-level brief — for example, that Working With Children Check verification happened completely separately from registration and was tracked in yet another spreadsheet maintained by a different volunteer.",
    "The technical architecture decision came down to a fundamental question: native apps versus cross-platform Flutter. The club's volunteer base skewed heavily Android but the coaching staff were largely iPhone users — a split that made native development uneconomical. Flutter gave us a single codebase with genuinely native-feeling UI on both platforms, and the club's requirements didn't include anything that would push against Flutter's limitations. For the backend we chose Node.js with PostgreSQL, a stack we could deploy cost-effectively on AWS and that any competent developer could maintain or extend in future without specialist knowledge.",
    "One early challenge was scope management. As we presented wireframes across the team, enthusiasm grew and the wishlist expanded quickly — a ladder tracker, a training drill library, live scores, player statistics going back years. We worked closely with the president and registrar to keep the first release focused on the three problems that genuinely hurt most: member management, fee collection, and roster communications. Everything else went on a clearly documented backlog with rough priority rankings that the committee could revisit after launch.",
    "The timeline from first discovery call to app store submission was sixteen weeks. The first eight weeks were design and backend architecture; the final eight were app development, integration testing, and a two-week parallel run where the registrar used both the new platform and the old spreadsheet simultaneously to validate that data was consistent. We deliberately scheduled go-live after the current season's registrations had already closed, so the first full season on the new platform was a clean start rather than a migration mid-year."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The core of the platform is a member management database built on PostgreSQL, with a Node.js REST API serving both the Flutter mobile app and a lightweight web-based admin dashboard accessible from any browser. Each member record holds personal details, emergency contacts, grade assignment, registration status, fee payment history, and document uploads including Working With Children Check numbers with expiry tracking. Administrators get an alert when any required document is within 60 days of expiry — a feature that turned out to be one of the most appreciated at the club's end-of-year AGM.",
    "Fee collection is handled through a Stripe integration that supports both card payments and direct debit via BECS, which matters in a community club context where many families prefer to set up a recurring payment rather than remember a one-off transaction. The app generates a payment link that can be shared via the notification system, and payment status is updated in real time via Stripe webhooks. The treasurer sees a live dashboard of outstanding, partial, and completed payments broken down by grade, with one-click export to CSV for their own records.",
    "Team rosters are managed by team managers within the app, with role-based permissions that give managers write access to their own team only while administrators retain oversight across all grades. Coaches receive push notifications via Firebase Cloud Messaging when roster changes are made, and can mark training attendance directly from their phone during the session itself. The attendance model is deliberately simple: a coach opens their team, sees the expected attendees for that session, and taps to mark each player present or absent. That data feeds back into the admin dashboard so the registrar can track participation trends over a season.",
    "The communication layer replaced the WhatsApp chaos with structured in-app push notifications and optional SMS delivery via Twilio for recipients who hadn't yet installed the app. Notifications can be targeted at a specific team, a specific grade, or the full membership, with delivery receipts visible to the sender. We intentionally kept this simple — the goal was reliable one-way communication from management to members, not a full social messaging platform that would have added complexity and cost without solving the core problem.",
    "AWS infrastructure is deliberately modest: an EC2 t3.small instance handles the API and admin dashboard behind an Application Load Balancer, RDS PostgreSQL on a db.t3.micro with automated daily snapshots, and S3 for document storage with server-side encryption. The monthly AWS bill runs to approximately $85, which the club budgeted into its annual fees without drama. Firebase handles push notifications at no meaningful cost at this scale. The entire stack is documented in a runbook that a reasonably technical volunteer committee member could follow to perform basic maintenance."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "Flutter", reason: "Single codebase for iOS and Android, matching the club's mixed-device volunteer base" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "Backend API — familiar, well-documented, easy for future maintainers to work with" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Relational data model suited to members, teams, grades, seasons, and payment records" },
    { name: "Stripe", reason: "Card and BECS direct debit, real-time webhooks, low transaction fees for non-profit context" },
    { name: "Firebase Cloud Messaging", reason: "Reliable push notifications to both iOS and Android without managing a separate notification service" },
    { name: "Twilio SMS", reason: "Fallback notification delivery for members who hadn't installed the app yet" },
    { name: "AWS EC2 + RDS", reason: "Cost-effective, well-understood hosting with automated backups and clear scaling path" },
    { name: "Amazon S3", reason: "Secure document storage for Working With Children Checks and registration forms" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "Rollout was structured around the club's off-season — the six weeks between the end of one season and the start of pre-season training for the next. We ran two in-person training sessions at the clubhouse: one for the four core administrators and one for team managers across all grades. Both sessions were hands-on, with everyone using test accounts on their own phones rather than watching a slideshow. We recorded both sessions and shared the recordings with committee members who couldn't attend in person.",
    "The member data migration was handled carefully. We exported the existing spreadsheet data, wrote a cleaning script to standardise formatting, and imported it into the new system with each member's record flagged as needing first-login verification. When members logged in for the first time, they were prompted to confirm their details were correct before proceeding — a lightweight data quality check that caught around 40 stale records. The club's registrar reviewed any records that members hadn't confirmed within three weeks and updated them manually where she had better information.",
    "Go-live was at the start of open registrations for the new season. Within the first four weeks, 94% of registrations were completed entirely through the app. The remaining 6% were families without smartphones — predominantly grandparents listed as primary contacts — who registered via a printed form that the registrar entered manually. We'd anticipated this and built an admin-side manual registration flow for exactly that reason. The club's committee described the first registration season as the smoothest they'd experienced in years."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The Working With Children Check tracking feature was added late in the project after a committee member raised it almost as an afterthought during sign-off review. It ended up being one of the most practically useful features in the platform. We've since built it into our discovery questionnaire for any project involving volunteer organisations in NSW, because SafeWork NSW and NSW Fair Trading expectations around volunteer screening aren't always top of mind for clients who are focused on the obvious operational problems.",
    "We underestimated how much emotional weight the treasurer carried around the fee collection problem. The spreadsheet wasn't just an administrative tool — it represented hours of personal effort over many years, and suggesting we were replacing it required more care than we initially gave it. In retrospect, we should have involved the treasurer more actively in the design of the payment dashboard rather than presenting it as a finished solution. The feature worked well technically, but the transition would have been smoother with more co-design.",
    "Parallel running the old spreadsheet alongside the new system for two weeks before go-live added real time and cost to the project, but it was absolutely the right call. We found three edge cases in the fee calculation logic that would have caused genuine discrepancies if they'd been discovered after families had already been issued payment requests. For volunteer-run clubs where trust is the social fabric, financial errors would have been particularly damaging. Any future project of this type will have that parallel validation phase written into the contract."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "In the six months following go-live, the club requested two significant additions: a grading assessment module that lets coaches record evaluations during pre-season trials, and an incident reporting feature that creates a timestamped record whenever a player sustains an injury during training or a match. The injury reporting module was partly driven by the club's insurer asking whether digital records were available following a claim, and partly by growing awareness among the committee of best-practice duty-of-care expectations.",
    "The club has since referred two other clubs in their district competition to All Webbed Labs. We're currently scoping a version of the platform that would support multiple clubs under a single administrative umbrella — a structure that would appeal to district rugby unions wanting to provide a shared technology service to member clubs without each club needing its own infrastructure budget."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "After a full season on the platform, the club's volunteer administrators collectively reclaimed roughly 180 hours that had previously been consumed by manual administrative tasks — time that several of them have redirected into coaching development and junior recruitment. The improvement in fee collection alone more than covered the cost of development within the first season, and the club entered its third year on the platform without a single missed registration deadline.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "60%", label: "Reduction in admin time", context: "Across all volunteer roles combined" },
    { value: "94%", label: "Fees collected on time", context: "Up from 71% in the previous season" },
    { value: "450", label: "Active app users", context: "Reached within the first month of launch" },
    { value: "3 hrs", label: "Saved per team manager weekly", context: "Across 8 team managers" },
    { value: "87%", label: "Coach satisfaction rating", context: "From post-season survey, n=8" },
    { value: "0", label: "Missed registration deadlines", context: "Since platform launch" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "Athlete Performance Tracking Platform",
      href: "/case-studies/athlete-performance-tracking",
